{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628006"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17159"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17159"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0.02,0.83,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113908"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9849"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17159"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95927"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8424"},{"type":"tags","id":"8425"},{"type":"tags","id":"10260"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23083"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113908"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle contains overlapping thick and thin filaments that form the contractile apparatus. The conversion of chemical energy from adenosine triphosphate (ATP) into mechanical work enables muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the essential role of the myosin head in muscle contraction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Degrades actin filaments","Synthesises ATP from ADP","Transports calcium ions","Performs power stroke on actin","Regulates tropomyosin position"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe essential function of the myosin head domain is to\u003Cstrong\u003E execute the power stroke on actin.\u003C/strong\u003E This process involves several key steps:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EATP binding to myosin causes detachment from actin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EATP hydrolysis enables myosin to cock into a high-energy state\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyosin rebinds to actin and releases phosphate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe power stroke occurs as myosin returns to its low-energy conformation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EADP release completes the cycle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDegrades actin filaments\u003C/strong\u003E - Actin filaments are stable structures that slide past myosin filaments during contraction without being broken down\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesises ATP from ADP\u003C/strong\u003E - Myosin consumes ATP rather than producing it. ATP synthesis occurs through oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransports calcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium transport is performed by specific ion channels and the calcium ATPase pump in the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulates tropomyosin position\u003C/strong\u003E - Tropomyosin movement is controlled by the troponin complex when it binds calcium, not by myosin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis cyclical interaction between myosin and actin, powered by ATP hydrolysis, is the fundamental mechanism that generates force in muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The myosin head domain converts chemical energy from ATP into mechanical force through the power stroke mechanism.","The cross-bridge cycle requires ATP both for force generation and for detachment of myosin from actin.","Repeated cycles of myosin-actin interaction drive muscle contraction at the molecular level."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95927"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17159"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95927"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T12:04:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T12:04:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9849"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113908"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data